author: @KrisBend
text:
Dwayne Johnson truly embodied Black Adam, bringing an intense and brooding presence to the role that we haven’t seen from him before. His performance alone is worth the watch!!!
The visual effects and action sequences were top-notch. The fight scenes were exhilarating and showcased Black Adam’s powers in a way that felt fresh and exciting!!!
And I was a bit disappointed with the plot. It felt like it had so much potential to dive deeper into Black Adam’s rich backstory but ended up focusing too much on spectacle over substance!!!

I'm actually going Give it a 8/10.. with top down explanation.

2.) They focused more on the character Ark of Black Adams.
3.) The Writing the Tropes were Not the greatest & Storyline was kind of sloppy..

If, they made 2 movies with the same energy, CGI & time to develop character arcs..

I would of given it a 9/10. 👏👏

author: @user-dr2yz8um3d
text:
Low and behold, the movie is 1 year old!!!

My most hyped up movie of the fall
Not as bad as many are making it
Violent but funny, exciting, opens more of the DCEU
Dwayne Johnson has a lot of charisma and Sarah Shahi and especially Pierce Brosnan as Dr. Fate
The team called the Justice Society of America is fun even if not all the members are fleshed out
Plus the action scenes are amazing and the plot is easy to follow despite a lot of slo mo and exposition next to the flashbacks
Great cameo too from a familiar actor from a previous film
A very weak villain though as you'd expect
Says a lot about having a champion in a 3rd world country as far as representation, diplomacy, heroism, choosing to be a destroyer or savior, being worthy of god like powers or not, being up to fate to decide our outcome
15 years of Johnson playing this character was worth the wait, this is one of my favorite DC comic book characters now

text:
Actually, this is one of my favourite superhero movies if not the most.
Number 1, Rock is one action I love.
Number 2, this movie is kinda similar to Batman, my favourite DC superhero. I know Batman do not kill, but Black Adam's story is just about as dark as Batman's. Shamefully, for many countries in poverty, and even developing countries, it have a lot of problems pictured here. Some of these countries are controlled by warlords and gangs, and some of them get environmental destruction problems due to big companies from developed countries. Quite unfair, but because of such problems are difficult to solve, and more importantly, have related benefits for companies in more developed countries, they get ignored quite a lot.
Example 1, rainforest destruction in South America and Indonesia largely due to big corporations and companies in the United States. Palm oil industry, which include forcing indigenous people to lose their lands and do excess labour. Related news can be found on Rainforest Action Network websites.
Example 2, recently, a lot of people in China meet con artists from Thailand and Burma, lose ten billions of RMB per year. And many Chinese people even got kidnapped through this way for ransom and organ trades. But, you know what? Such trades could only happen because of there are a lot of Chinese members among such con artist groups! How painful is that! And for those drug dealers, conartists groups, military gangs, they are too powerful for local government to control. Not only that, because they have both local power and Chinese people in their teams, they have people work for them among local police force, and very likely also inside Chinese governments.

I study biology, and that includes a bit about environment and society, so I know the world pictured here is very true. And for people in those countries, they really do need heroes like Black Adam here to free them.

author: @redbunnytail9528
text: When you see 'Black Adam' for the 2nd time, and it really does take more than one screening to have a grasp of story, emotions, and where it fits in the collective fantasy worlds, so you can have an informed opinion. Many things I didn't see the first time on the plane, with the little screen staring back at me. Now. At home. Big computer screen and I can see all the things I missed. I can see why many actors are into this idea of how movies are weaker than they used to be. They're talking about themselves. You know? Movies are getting astronomically more skilled at making impossible realities, come true. Johnson is not a spring chicken, but he pulls a LOT of weight as a fantasy, comic book hero, on screen. And THAT will give an actor confidence. Brosnan and Hodge were really packing it, in 'Black Adam.' Everything I heard, about 'BA' made me predict a horrible movie, and really happy I was 100 percent off the mark. THIS is an awesome movie. Johnson and Cavill no longer planning any more movies is too bad. But. You can go really far with a dude like Hodge. He's basically a foundation to build on, if DC wants a quick way to their version of Marvel's 'End Game.' Whoever came up with this 'version' of Hawkman is WAY beyond me. Like light years beyond me. And I'm really into comic book worlds. Great job.

author: @wolfirene1967
text: Loved the seriousness of the Rock. Such an underrated actor. This movie did not take the time to develop the other characters except for the clear crushes of our young heroes. Great chemistry.The visuals were amazing! I never read the comic book so have no idea who they all are. Still don't after watching the movie. I understood who Black Adam was but not the other characters. The one thing I could NOT stand is the soundtrack. Too loud in many places where it should have been soft. What I mean is, sequences that had no REAL action, just characters talking, should not be accompanied by an  'action' soundtrack, especially one heavy with a horn section. A Horn section is serious business and should be saved for a climatic scene. Very bad choice. Good lord, it was distracting. Sound tracks are meant to control the viewer's emotions and they totally missed the mark. Gone are the years of John Williams and Danny Elfman of my time. However,  this was an improvement over Wonder Woman 1984. The only part I enjoyed of that movie is Gail Gadot, I can't even imagine another actress doing Wonder Woman ever again, she's perfect. Dear WB, give Gadot a better script!!

author: @willbrink
text: The only good thing about this super hero movie is The Rock who plays his character perfectly. Everything else is pretty much over produced trash. The CGI is clunky and poorly done in parts, and that's unforgivable in a modern movie with an approx 200 million dollar budget. The dialogue ranges from witty  to generic predictable super hero ra ra nonsense. The plot is without any original ideas, and the super heroes sent to battle Adam lame all around. The actors themselves all do a decent job with what they are given (fun to see Pierce Brosnan as Dr. Fate) but it can't save this movie. The Superman cameo at the end was a missed opportunity but now that  Cavill is no longer Superman, they will not be able to follow up with the set up for a battle between them. C-

Can we take a moment to appreciate all the symbolism of the oppression of Palestine and it’s people?

Johnson plays the role of Black Adam. Amon tells Black Adam that ever since his death, his country has been subjected to numerous invaders and oppression. That his people have been waiting for the return of Black Adam.

In Biblical terms, Jesus is referred to as The New Adam. He is considered the Savior (in Christian culture) who will have a second coming (both in Christian and Islamic cultures). Palestine has been a country invaded by the Greeks, Romans, etc and its people have been subjected to imperialism and oppression. Today, by the Israeli regime, a self-imposed state (not to be confused with the religious or ethnic Jews, though many Jews do live there) which denies Palestinian people freedom, peace, and equal treatment as citizens of the land.

Awesome symbolism!

author: @skmreviewvlogs5896
text:
* Black Adam Movie Review **

Directed by Jaume Collet - Serra starring Dwayne Johnson , Pierce Brosnan , Sarah Shahi , Aldis Hodge , Noah Centineo , Quintessa Swindell

Plot of the Movie...

2600 BC, a place called Kahndhq , where the dark dominates the poor, a fearless boy comes as a protector, as a hero but the mission goes incomplete....

In the present day, Kahndhq is still not free from darkness and time comes for the protector to come back and he is back....

Now is he really a hero ??? Really the protector, people of Kahndhq were looking upon?? Questions many....

Analysis of the Movie...

1) Action, action, action... Dwayne from his fast and furious action had elevated his action in the sky by swriling the baddies up in the air, mercilessly throwing away them like a garbage into the land, with his electrifying hand turns the baddies into a handful of skeleton...Ufffffff it was thunderous....

2) Action sequences were the main highlight where the hawkman- Adam one on one fights was just goosebumps for me....

3) Dr Fate, the man who executes his action in his stylish, calm way....

4) VFX of Hollywood always always fascinates me, as it gives us the manifestation of the unbelievable to be believable...

&&&&& Finally the end credits.... Raised double goosebumps 🔥🔥🔥🔥

Black Adam, an out an out action entertainer package movie

author: @Roughneck8
text:
Just a few things, you don't have to agree:

Tired of Rock's movies, also just tired of The Rock. Have fond memories of watching him wrestling growing up, watching The Rundown, Walking Tall, Scorpion King in theaters at like 11..but enough.

Looks awful, looks woke, but doesn't only look awful because of it's wokeness, just looks unintriguing, feels like something I've seen a hundred times in many different films.

I am not familiar with and have no understanding of "Black Adam," sounds kinda racially charged. To someone like me it kind of sounds like there's a religious connotation to the name, which I would find disrespectful to the original tale and dismissive for the superhero character and it's actor. This is probably not the case, just what a casual passerby like me may think upon first glimpse.

That's all, thanks for your time.

author: @cooldvijay1
text:
The Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC) was an ancient Greek war fought between Athens and Sparta and their respective allies for the hegemony of the Greek world. The war remained undecided for a long time until the decisive intervention of the Persian Empire in support of Sparta. Led by Lysander, the Spartan fleet built with Persian subsidies finally defeated Athens and started a period of Spartan hegemony over Greece.

Historians have traditionally divided the war into three phases. The first phase (431–421 BC) was named the Ten Years War, or the Archidamian War, after the Spartan king Archidamus II, who launched several invasions of Attica with the full hoplite army of the Peloponnesian League, the alliance network dominated by Sparta. However, the Long Walls of Athens rendered this strategy ineffective, while the superior navy of the Delian League (Athens' alliance) raided the Peloponnesian coast to trigger rebellions within Sparta. The precarious Peace of Nicias was signed in 421 BC and lasted until 413 BC. Several proxy battles took place during this period, notably the battle of Mantinea in 418 BC, won by Sparta against an ad-hoc alliance of Elis, Mantinea (both former Spartan allies), Argos and Athens. The main event was nevertheless the Sicilian Expedition between 415 and 413 BC, during which Athens lost almost all its navy in the attempted capture of Syracuse, an ally in Sparta.

The Sicilian disaster prompted the third phase of the war (413–404 BC), named the Decelean War, or the Ionian War, when the Persian Empire supported Sparta in order to recover the suzerainty of the Greek cities of Asia Minor, incorporated into the Delian League at the end of the Persian Wars. With Persian money, Sparta built a massive fleet under the leadership of Lysander, who won a streak of decisive victories in the Aegean Sea, notably at Aegospotamos in 405 BC. Athens capitulated the following year and lost all its empire; Lysander imposed puppet oligarchies on the former members of the Delian League, including Athens, where the regime was known as the Thirty Tyrants. The Peloponnesian War was followed ten years later by the Corinthian War (394–386 BC), which, although it ended inconclusively, helped Athens regain its independence from Sparta.

The Peloponnesian War reshaped the ancient Greek world. On the level of international relations, Athens, the strongest city-state in Greece prior to the war's beginning, was reduced to a state of near-complete subjection, while Sparta became established as the leading power of Greece. The economic costs of the war were felt all across Greece; poverty became widespread in the Peloponnese, while Athens was completely devastated, and never regained its pre-war prosperity.[2][3] The war also wrought subtler changes to Greek society; the conflict between democratic Athens and oligarchic Sparta, each of which supported friendly political factions within other states, made war a common occurrence in the Greek world. Ancient Greek warfare, meanwhile, originally a limited and formalized form of conflict, was transformed into an all-out struggle between city-states, complete with atrocities on a large scale. Shattering religious and cultural taboos, devastating vast swathes of countryside, and destroying whole cities, the Peloponnesian War marked the dramatic end to the fifth century BC and the golden age of Greece.[4]

author: @LordZandersSoapbox4811
text: This isn’t Black Adam, it’s a revisionist fan fiction.  In the DC Comic books, Black Adam is one of the most powerful supervillains in the Universe. He’s not the Anti-Villain, living to avenge his son, shown in this trailer. In the comics he has murdered family, even children, to gain power. As a fan of DC comic books, when all is said and done, he only cares about power. I accept the fact that WB is not making these movies for me but for the “normies” and consumer fans of the DCEU.
